article.headline: Randolph adds 26, nine rebounds
article.linkText: Nets loss: Stoudamire's 28 blaze trail to win
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers badly need some leadership -- on and off of the court. Damon Stoudamire wants to provide both. Stoudamire had a season-high 28 points on 12-of-17 shooting and seven assists Friday night, and the Blazers rallied in the fourth quarter to defeat the New Jersey Nets 97-93. Portland is 8-7 this season, with all eight wins coming at the Rose Garden, but off-the-court turmoil continues to overshadow the play on the floor. Rasheed Wallace was replaced in coach Maurice Cheeks' starting lineup Friday after missing a team shootaround earlier that morning. Wallace told Cheeks that he had overslept. He entered at the start of the second quarter and had 11 points and 10 rebounds in 29 minutes, and is expected to be fined. With Qyntel Woods starting in Wallace's place, Stoudamire said he felt he needed to take charge. "I'm just trying to be encouraging because we have this big cloud over us," he said. "It's always there; I am just trying to get people to have fun again." Stoudamire, who was averaging just 12 points a game this season, made three of six 3-pointers in 45 minutes. Jason Kidd had 27 points on 12-of-18 shooting and seven assists to lead the Nets, whose two-game road winning streak was snapped. Zach Randolph had 26 points and nine rebounds for Portland. Jeff McInnis added 18 points. Portland trailed the entire second half -- seven at the start of the fourth quarter -- until Stoudamire hit a long jumper with 4:43 left to give the Blazers a 87-85 lead. Portland then went on a 9-6 run, capped by a 3-pointer by Stoudamire, to make it 96-91 with 40.5 seconds left. "My most satisfying win since I've been here, I think," Cheeks said. "It looked like we were just climbing the hill and not getting over the top, but then they missed a few shots and we started hitting ours and all of a sudden we were in control." After a basket by Kidd, Stoudamire made a free throw to seal the victory. "We just couldn't get any stops in the fourth quarter and they took command," Kidd said. Lucious Harris scored 15 points for the Nets, all in the first half. Jason Collins also had 15 points. Bonzi Wells had no points and four fouls in 17 minutes and hasn't started since returning from a two-game suspension earlier this week. He was loudly booed upon entering the game at the end of the first quarter. "It's frustrating to always hear people down on us as a team," Stoudamire said. "Everybody's played their fair share in it, but at the end of the day we are human beings, too. When Bonzi gets booed, I can feel that."

Game notes
Portland had its six-game winning streak at the Rose Garden snapped with Tuesday's 81-80 loss to Washington. ... Robert Pack, cut by Portland in training camp, is averaging 3.0 points and 2.3 assists in three games for New Jersey. ... The Nets are just 5-24 at Portland.
